urghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Skotland","Battle of Hastings Sussex England":"Battle, Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Overleden","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1033–1066":"1033–1066","1046–Female":"1046–Overleden","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","1046":"1046","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1033":"1033","1130":"1130","14 Oct 1066":"1066","Seine Maritime Haute Normandy France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Frankrijk","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Schotland","Battle of Hastings Sussex England":"Battle, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Deceased","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1033–1066":"1033–1066","1046–Female":"1046–Deceased","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","1046":"1046","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1033":"1033","1130":"1130","14 Oct 1066":"1066","Seine Maritime Haute Normandy France":"Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Battle of Hastings Sussex England":"Battle, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Colville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Colleville in Seine-Maritime, France, named with the Scandinavian personal name <i>Koli</i> (see   Cole   2) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement, village’. The Scottish branch of the family were descended from Philip <i>de Colville</i>, who came to Scotland as a household knight of kings Malcolm IV (1153–65) and William ‘the Lion’ (1165–1214)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cole","meanings":["English: usually from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Col(e)</i>, <i>Coll(e)</i>, <i>Coul(e)</i>, a pet form of <i>Nicol</i> (see   Nichol   and   Nicholas  ), a common personal name from the mid 13th century onward. English families with this name migrated to Scotland and to Ulster (especially Fermanagh).","English: occasionally perhaps from a different (early) Middle English personal name <i>Col</i>, of native English or Scandinavian origin. Old English <i>Cola</i> was originally a nickname from Old English <i>col</i> ‘coal’ in the sense ‘coal-black (of hair), swarthy’ and is the probable source of most of the examples in Domesday Book. In the northern and eastern counties of England settled by Vikings in the 10th and 11th centuries, alternative sources are Old Norse <i>Kolr</i> and <i>Koli</i> (either from a nickname ‘the swarthy one’ or a short form of names in <i>Kol-</i>), and Old Norse <i>Kollr</i> (from a nickname, perhaps ‘the bald one’).","English: nickname for someone with swarthy skin or black hair, from Middle English <i>col</i>, coul(e) ‘charcoal, coal’ (Old English <i>col</i>)."]},{"name":"Colvin","meanings":["Scottish and Irish (Donegal, Antrim): variant of   Colville  , probably reflecting a local pronunciation. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th century.","Manx: if not identical with 1, perhaps from the Old Norse personal name <i>Kolbeinn</i>, with /v/ substituted for /b/.","English: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Colwin</i>, <i>Colvin</i>, which may be a borrowing into English of a Welsh name whose modern form is <i>Collwyn</i> ‘white’, or of <i>colwyn</i> ‘doe, puppy, pet dog’, or of the placename <i>Colwyn</i> (Denbighshire, Radnorshire)."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert De  Colville was born in 1066, in Seine-Maritime, Upper Normandy, France, his father, Gilbert De Colville I, was 33 and his mother, Mrs Gilbert de Colville, was 21. He had at least 1 son with Margaret Lindsay. He died in 1130, at the age of 64."},"et":{"1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1033–1066":"1033–1066","1046–Female":"1046–Surnud","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","1046":"1046","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1033":"1033","1130":"1130","14 Oct 1066":"1066","Seine Maritime Haute Normandy France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Battle of Hastings Sussex England":"Battle, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1066–1130":"1066–1130","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1100–1159":"1100–1159","1033–1066":"1033–1066","1046–Female":"1046–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1159":"1159","1046":"1046","1100":"1100","1066":"1066","1033":"1033","1130":"1130","14 Oct 1066":"1066","Seine Maritime Haute Normandy France":"Seine-Maritime, Haute-Normandie, Ranska","Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland":"Oxnam, Roxburghshire, Scotland","Battle of Hastings Sussex England":"Battle, Sussex, Englanti, Yhd